[3] Sierra Leone: Shock treatment missing from Ebola response
Date: Sun 14 Dec 2014
Source: Yahoo News, Reuters report [edited]
http://news.yahoo.com/shock-treatment-whats-missing-sierra-leones-ebola-response-161543551.html


Shock treatment: what's missing from Sierra Leone's Ebola response
------------------------------------------------------------------
The failure of Sierra Leone's strategy for fighting Ebola may be down to a missing ingredient: a big shock that changes people's behavior and prevents further infections. "Every new place that gets infected goes through that learning curve, where a lot of people die before those behaviors [which are associated with transmission of infection] start to change," Bruce Aylward, the head of Ebola response at the World Health Organisation said.

While neighbouring Liberia has turned the tide of Ebola, and both Mali and Nigeria quickly smothered outbreaks, Sierra Leone [now] has more than 70 percent of cases reported in the past 3 weeks and more than half the 18 000 confirmed [sic: in fact, many fewer confirmed] cases in the 9-month-old outbreak.

The flare-up in Sierra Leone capital Freetown and the country's more heavily populated western areas resemble the massive infections suffered in August [2014] by Liberian capital Monrovia. Scenes of people dying in the street raised alarm across that country and prompted a military deployment by the United States to build treatment centers. "In Monrovia you had bodies on the streets, and then awareness went through the roof in a very, very short time as a result," said Aylward.

Mali also learned through a shock. Just as it seemed nobody had been infected by its 1st Ebola patient in October [2014], another cluster of deaths sprang up the following month [September 2014]. Aylward said he told Malian officials that the only way to stop the outbreak was to trace anyone who may be at risk. "That's when the contact tracing took a jump from around 60-70 percent completion to 98 percent," he said.

In Sierra Leone, where as many as 365 Ebola deaths may have been linked to a single traditional funeral [of a traditional healer] early in the epidemic, Sierra Leone's Health Minister Abu Bakarr Fofanah said the government was considering banning some unsafe practices. He recognized however that it would be difficult to police such a law. Fofanah noted that some areas of eastern Sierra Leone that were hit hardest early in the epidemic -- around the towns of Kenema and Kailahun -- have seen a massive reduction in case numbers as people change behavior. "The areas that are now doing badly are the areas that were affected last. They are still on the learning curve." ... -- more

[Byline: Tom Miles]

